{"source_key":"sha256-c8597aca71664a84bdd657ea13dadbd3","record_index":1285,"record_hash":"sha256:71c25e026bb06c3f82595e32b7fa99bdc308cd3ce3f18a09bb0ba456619d7c04","timestamp":"2026-05-20T02:30:01.711Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 5ba619\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 1382\nOutput:\n# Including Turns In Agentlog\n\nThis note explores an evolution of `but-agentlog`: add a durable concept of an\nagent session turn between the project-scoped session and the captured transcript\nrecords.\n\nThe motivation is the session-association problem. The older\n[Session Association Strategy](session-association-strategy.md) is right to be\ncautious about capture-time ownership, but it treats the captured session mostly\nas one coarse object. In practice, the hook flow already gives us a more useful\nunit: every stop hook invocation is effectively a capture after an agent turn.\n\nToday `but-agentlog` deduplicates transcript records into one project session:\n\n```text\nproject session -> transcript records\n```\n\nThat stores the conversation, but it loses which newly observed records belonged\nto which capture invocation. It also loses the repository state that was true at\nthat moment. A turn layer would preserve that missing context without forcing us\nto immediately claim that the session \"belongs\" to a branch, commit, change, or\npull request.\n\n## Product Use Cases\n\nKeep this grounded in the same two use cases as the rest of the agent-session\ncapture project.\n\n### 1. Session Handoff\n\nHandoff wants enough project-scoped session context to continue work on another\nmachine or with another agent. For this use case, turns help because they add\nstructure:\n\n- the session can be reconstructed as a sequence of user/agent interactions\n- a future reader can see the repository state around each interaction\n- consumers can choose the latest turn, a specific turn, or a window of turns\n  instead of treating the whole transcript as one flat blob\n\nHandoff does not necessarily need branch association. It mostly needs readable\nconversation records, ordering, and enough environment context to orient the\nnext agent.\n\n### 2. Review Sharing\n\nReview sharing wants a GitButler web view that can show reviewers what happened\nbehind a branc\n[TRUNCATED]\nobserved this time.\"\n\nEvery time the capture flow runs:\n\n1. parse the transcript snapshot\n2. deduplicate against already stored record hashes\n3. append only new transcript records\n4. write a turn object describing this capture invocation\n5. record which transcript records belong to the turn\n6. record enough repository environment state to support later association\n\nCreate a session turn only when capture writes at least one new transcript\nrecord. An environment-only observation should not create a turn. Otherwise the\nmodel drifts from agent-session capture into repository telemetry.\n\nThe first hook run for a session may capture more than one actual conversation\nturn if it imports an existing transcript backlog. Later stop-hook runs should\nusually map more closely to one user/agent interaction. That distinction should\nstay visible in the model: a turn is a capture observation, not necessarily a\nprovider-native turn.\n\nFor first-time backfill, create one capture turn containing all newly written\nrecords and one environment snapshot from capture time. Provider-native turn\nidentifiers, when available, can be preserved as optional record-level grouping\nmetadata, but they should not become real session turns during backfill because\nhistorical repository environment snapshots cannot be reconstructed.\n\nStore a compact `capture_kind` on the turn:\n\n- `backfill`: the capture imported an existing transcript backlog\n- `incremental`: the capture observed new records from an ongoing session\n\nBackfill turns are valid transcript history, but their environment snapshot is\nweaker association evidence because it only describes capture time, not the time\neach historical provider turn happened.\n\nBackfill must still be readable. Record parsing should preserve enough grouping\nmetadata for handoff and review UIs to render logical conversation turns inside\nthe backfill capture turn:\n\n- provider turn key when the source provides one\n- otherwise a derived display group based on user-message boundaries and record\n  order\n\n## Turn Data\n\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T02:30:01.711Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}